# CXLFS service

The service keeps exactly one authoritative filesystem image in a fixed
per-machine slice of a dedicated CXL-like QEMU ivshmem device.  The device is
backed by `/dev/shm/ivshmem-cxlfs-$USER`; its eight fixed 1 GiB slices are
addressed by machine id and are not managed by the application CXL or DRAM
allocators.  The device contains a disk format: two superblock slots,
inode/block bitmaps, a fixed inode table, directory records, and 4 KiB data and
indirect blocks.  Every persistent reference is an inode or block number.

`struct inode`, dentries, hash/radix indices, vnode/fd tables, and reference
counts are private runtime state.  Mount recursively rebuilds them from the CXL
directory records; file contents are read and written directly in the CXL
image.  Overwrites allocate and flush a new data block before switching the
inode block number and publishing the alternate superblock generation.

The separate 4 MiB p-log contains only redo operations newer than the last
checkpoint.  `fsync` (and log-capacity rollover) publishes and flushes the CXL
superblock first and truncates the p-log last.  Recovery mounts the stable image,
rebuilds volatile indices, and replays the untruncated redo tail.  No process
virtual address is part of either persistent format.

Create the device once with `./dsm-scripts/prepare_cxlfs_dev.sh`.  Subsequent
launches require the existing 8 GiB device and never recreate, resize, or clear
it.  `CXLFS_DEV` can override the device path; its size remains fixed at 8 GiB.
